      <p>Selling a deceased estate property is not like selling your own home. The executor carries legal responsibilities that go beyond simply choosing an agent and accepting an offer. The process is shaped by probate requirements, the terms of the will, the number of beneficiaries involved, and Queensland property law. Understanding what is required before you engage an agent can save months of delay and significant cost.</p>

      <p>This guide is written for executors managing a deceased estate in Brisbane and Queensland more broadly. It covers the legal steps before you can sell, what happens when multiple beneficiaries are involved, how to choose the right agent, and the common points where things slow down or go wrong.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Probate: the first step before anything else</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, probate is the formal legal process through which the Supreme Court confirms the validity of a will and grants the executor authority to deal with the deceased's assets. If the estate includes real property, you will almost certainly need to obtain probate before you can transfer or sell it. A solicitor handles the probate application; it is not something an agent can assist with.</p>

      <p>The timeline for probate in Queensland varies. In straightforward cases with a clear will, it can take six to eight weeks from application to grant. In contested matters or where the will cannot be located, it can take considerably longer. During this period, the property cannot be sold, though you can begin preparing it and engaging an agent to plan the campaign. Some agents will have worked with deceased estates before and understand this staging; it is worth asking.</p>

      <p>Once probate is granted, the executor has the legal authority to sell. If there is no will, the court appoints an administrator to manage the estate under the rules of intestacy, and that administrator holds equivalent authority once appointed. Your solicitor will confirm when the appropriate authority is in place and you can proceed.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the executor can and cannot do</h2>
      <p>Once probate is granted, the executor has broad authority to deal with estate property, including appointing an agent, setting an asking price or reserve, accepting or rejecting offers, and signing contracts. The executor does not need approval from each beneficiary before accepting an offer, unless the will specifically requires it or a court order imposes that condition.</p>

      <p>However, executors have a legal duty to act in the best interests of all beneficiaries, not in their own interest or the interest of a single beneficiary. This means the executor should not sell to a family member at below-market value, should not accept an unusually low offer without proper market testing, and should document the basis on which decisions were made. Working with an agent who understands this accountability is important, because the executor can be personally liable if the estate suffers a loss through poor decision-making.</p>

      <p>In practice, this means running a proper marketing campaign rather than selling off-market to avoid inconvenience, getting an independent appraisal before setting a price, and keeping clear records of all offers received and how the decision to accept was made.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When multiple beneficiaries are involved</h2>
      <p>Multiple beneficiaries do not have a legal right to individually approve or block the sale, but they do have the right to expect the executor to act properly. Where beneficiaries are in conflict, that conflict can lead to legal challenges that delay settlement or void a contract. This is one of the most common sources of delay in deceased estate sales.</p>

      <p>The most effective approach is to communicate clearly with all beneficiaries before and during the campaign. Explain the process, the pricing rationale, and how decisions will be made. This does not mean seeking approval for every decision, but it does mean not surprising people. A beneficiary who feels informed is far less likely to challenge the process than one who discovers the property has been sold without any communication.</p>

      <p>If beneficiaries genuinely cannot agree on whether to sell or what price to accept, the executor may need to seek directions from the Supreme Court. This is expensive and time-consuming, and it is worth exhausting every avenue for communication and mediation before taking that path.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing the property for sale</h2>
      <p>Deceased estate properties often require more preparation than an owner-occupied home. They may have been held for a long time, contain personal possessions that need to be cleared, and have deferred maintenance that the previous owner was unable or unwilling to address. Buyers will discount accordingly, and that discount is often larger than the actual cost to fix the issues.</p>

      <p>A practical approach is to engage a clearing company or auction house for personal effects first, then assess the property's physical condition. Focus on items that buyers will notice during an inspection: the condition of the kitchen and bathrooms, external paintwork, fencing, and garden presentation. In Brisbane's inner east, where buyers expect a certain standard of presentation, a neglected garden and peeling paintwork on an otherwise solid property can suppress the result by more than the cost to remedy them.</p>

      <p>Get building and pest reports done before you list, not after an offer is received. In a deceased estate, where the executor has limited knowledge of the property's history, a pre-sale inspection gives buyers confidence and removes a common reason for price renegotiation after contract.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Choosing the right agent</h2>
      <p>Not every agent has experience with deceased estates, and that experience matters. You want an agent who understands the probate process, can communicate clearly with multiple beneficiaries, is comfortable advising an executor rather than a straightforward vendor, and will document the campaign properly in case decisions are ever questioned.</p>

      <p>Ask agents directly whether they have sold deceased estate properties before and what the specific challenges were. Ask how they would handle a situation where beneficiaries disagreed with the pricing decision. The answers will tell you a lot about whether they understand the difference between a standard residential sale and an estate sale.</p>

      <p>The right agent will also be clear with you about market conditions. Executors sometimes feel pressure to accept the first reasonable offer to avoid prolonging the estate administration. That is understandable, but it is not always in the best interests of the beneficiaries. An agent who understands their obligations will give you an honest read on whether an early offer reflects market value or whether running the full campaign is likely to produce a materially better result.</p>

